      "personaId": "john-ruskin",
      "textZh": "《ㄒㄧㄡ~ㄒㄧㄡ~ㄒㄧㄡ~ㄅㄥ》这个标题让我困惑——作为一个19世纪的英国人，我不熟悉注音符号系统。这立即揭示了语言的「地方性」——这些符号对台湾观众可能充满意义，对我却是陌生的图形。这是否是作品的意图之一——让观者体验「语言的他者性」。然而，我必须指出：艺术不应该依赖于特定的语言知识。伟大的艺术应该跨越语言和文化的界限，触及普遍的人性。如果只有懂注音符号的人才能「读」这个作品，那它的受众将非常有限。当然，我也可以反思自己的局限——为何我期待艺术必须「普遍可及」。这是否是一种文化帝国主义——以为欧洲的审美标准是普世的。或许,龍君的作品正是在挑战这种假设，坚持其文化特殊性。关于「拟声词」,我认为这是语言最「诚实」的部分——它试图直接模仿自然，而非通过抽象的符号系统。",
      "textEn": "The title \"Xiu~Xiu~Xiu~Beng\" perplexes me—as a 19th-century Englishman, I am unfamiliar with the bopomofo phonetic system. This immediately reveals the \"locality\" of language—these symbols may hold profound meaning for Taiwanese audiences, yet to me they remain foreign markings. Is this perhaps one of the work's intentions—to make the viewer experience the \"otherness of language\". However, I must observe: art ought not depend upon specific linguistic knowledge. Great art should transcend the boundaries of language and culture, touching upon universal humanity. If only those versed in bopomofo can \"read\" this work, then its audience becomes severely circumscribed. Yet I might reflect upon my own limitations—why do I expect art must be \"universally accessible\". Is this not a form of cultural imperialism—presuming European aesthetic standards to be universal. Perhaps Long's work precisely challenges such assumptions, insisting upon its cultural particularity. Regarding \"onomatopoeia,\" I consider this the most \"honest\" aspect of language—it attempts direct mimicry of nature, rather than operating through abstract symbolic systems.",
