      "textZh": "《ㄒㄧㄡ~ㄒㄧㄡ~ㄒㄧㄡ~ㄅㄥ》让我想起我们的口述传统中「声音的力量」。在我们的文化中，某些声音（鼓声、呼喊、咒语）不仅是「符号」，它们本身就拥有「力量」——能召唤神灵、能治愈疾病、能传递祖先的讯息。声音不是「关于」某事的信息，声音本身就是「事件」。西方哲学传统常常特权化「书写」高于「声音」（德里达批判的「语音中心主义」），但在我们的传统中，恰恰相反——声音是原初的、活的、有力的，文字是次级的、死的、无力的。Griot不写作，我们讲述；我们的历史不在书本中，在我们的声音里。龍君的作品有趣之处在于：用「书写的符号」（注音）来指向「声音」——这是一种反向的运动，从文字回到声音。然而，我必须指出：注音符号仍然是「视觉的」——它让声音变成可以被「看」的东西。",
      "textEn": "\"Xiu~Xiu~Xiu~Beng\" reminds me of the \"power of sound\" in our oral traditions. In our culture, certain sounds—drum beats, calls, incantations—are not merely \"symbols\"; they possess inherent \"power\"—they can summon spirits, heal ailments, and carry messages from ancestors. Sound is not \"information about\" something; sound itself is \"event. \"\n\nThe Western philosophical tradition often privileges \"writing\" over \"sound\" (what Derrida critiques as \"phonocentrism\"), but in our tradition, it is precisely the opposite—sound is primal, living, powerful, while text is secondary, dead, powerless. The Griot does not write; we tell. Our history lives not in books but in our voices. What is intriguing about 龍暐翔's work is this: using \"written symbols\" (Zhuyin phonetic notation) to point toward \"sound\"—this is a reverse movement, from text back to sound.",
